  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(48) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Took a spunge, and filled it with vinegar.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The “vinegar” was the sour wine, or wine and water, which was the common drink of the Roman soldiers. and which they at an earlier stage, and as in derision (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 23:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), had offered to the Sufferer. The sponge had probably served instead of a cork to the jar in which the soldiers had brought the drink that was to sustain them in their long day’s work. Some one, whether soldier or Jew we know not, heard, not only the cry, “Eli, Eli, . . .” but the faint “I thirst,” which St. John records as coming from the fevered lips (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and prompted by a rough pity, stretched out a cane, or stalk of hyssop (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), with the sponge that had been dipped in the wine upon it, and bore it to the parched lips of the Sufferer. It was not now refused (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And gave him to drink.—The Greek verb is in the imperfect tense, as implying that while he was doing this, the others tried to interrupt him.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And gave him to drink.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The Greek verb is in the imperfect tense, as implying that while he was doing this, the others tried to interrupt him.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
