  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 27:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f. A touch of sympathy on the part of some one who had been moved by the painful cry of Jesus, and who would fain relieve Him by reaching Him a cordial. What a contrast to this in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 27:49",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "! According to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Jesus expressly intimated that He was thirsty. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 15:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " makes it appear that the person who reached the drink to Jesus was also one of those who were mocking Him, a discrepancy which we should make no attempt to reconcile, and in which we can have no difficulty in detecting traces of a more corrupt tradition. Luke omits this incident altogether, though in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 23:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he states that by way of mocking our Lord the soldiers ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "offered",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Him the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "posca",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " just ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "before",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the darkness came on. Strauss takes advantage of these discrepancies so as to make it appear that they are but different applications of the prediction contained in Psalms 69, without, however, disputing the fact that drink had been given to Jesus on two different occasions.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὄξους",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
